<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-409-608  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 409 608.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Executive  Spring 1990 v3 n2 p38(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Higher education: coming around to competitive systems.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ryland, Jane N.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Colleges and universities compete individually for students,faculty, and staff, and collectively against private industry andother nations.andP;  Students are increasingly recognized as customers,and information systems are increasingly structured to cater totheir needs more effectively.andP;  The competitive value of executiveinformation systems is increasingly recognized by colleges anduniversities, and flatter organizational structures are possibleas information becomes more readily available.andP;  Competitivesystems are achieving their best potential in environments ofdistributed, end-user computing because opening access to endusers increases chances that new ways of using existing technologyfor competitive advantage will be found.andP;  Integrated studentinformation systems are increasingly seen as key elements inattracting and retaining students, and the key elements of suchsystems are broad scope, consistency, and timeliness.andP;  There arecurrently systems in higher education that let students accesstheir own records electronically, provide voice processingcapabilities, enable registration via touchtone telephone, andlink information retrieval systems between schools.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information SystemsColleges and UniversitiesTrendsCompetition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>